(47, 'Birman ', 'birman', 'licensed-image (1).jpg', '<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(74, 69, 66)\">The Birman is a cat of distinction as well as legend. With their exotic ancestry, luxurious pointed coats, &ldquo;white-gloved&rdquo; paws, and mesmerizing blue eyes, this is a breed with undeniable charisma.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Temperament</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">The Birman&rsquo;s sweet and gentle nature makes her an ideal companion and pet. Birmans are playful and love to be with people, and are also patient and social with children and other pets.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">While Birmans tend to be fairly quiet, they will &ldquo;talk&rdquo; with soft, chirping voices. They enjoy the attention and want to be where their people are, helping with whatever activity is happening.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Characteristics</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">This healthy, long-lived breed has an outstanding, semi-long silky coat and a luxurious, long bottle-brush tail. Brilliant blue, almost-round eyes are prominent features of her sweet expression.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Lifespan</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">15+ years</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Colors</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birman coats can be seen in any pointed color: seal point, blue point, chocolate point, lilac point, or tortie point.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Shedding</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birmans are a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-breeds/collections/cat-breeds-with-moderate-shedding\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">moderate-shedding breed</a>. Their coats have no undercoat and are not prone to matting, so they require only weekly grooming with a stainless steel comb to keep shedding under control.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Health</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birmans are generally healthy cats, especially from a reputable breeder. Like many other cat breeds, they are at risk for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, the most common type of heart disease in cats. Responsible breeders will screen for this genetic condition, but it may not develop in cats until later in life.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Best Cat Food for Birman Cats &amp; Kittens</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birmans will generally thrive on the nutrition of quality&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-food/dry\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">adult cat food</a>. For Birmans who need help with weight management, consider a&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-family:inherit\"><a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-food/healthy-weight\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">healthy weight formula</a>.&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birman kittens should eat a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-food/kitten-food\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">kitten&#39;s food</a>&nbsp;for their first year of life to aid in their growth and development.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>History</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">The Birman legend begins in the temples of Burma (now Myanmar), where their ancestors were said to be the carriers of the souls of departed priests.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Around the beginning of the 20<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, a pair of Birman cats were transported from Burma to France. Sadly, the male cat died during the ocean voyage, but the female arrived pregnant with his offspring, bringing the Birman breed to Europe.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">The breed almost became extinct after WWII, but breeders revived it. The Birman breed arrived in the United States in 1959 and was registered with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cfa.org/\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\" target=\"_blank\">The Cat Fanciers&rsquo; Association (CFA)</a>&nbsp;in 1967.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Facts</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">A cat of mystery and legend, the Birman was the sacred cat of Burma, believed to be the&nbsp;companion of the priests of the temple.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Like all color point cats, Birman kittens are born all white and develop their color as they&nbsp;mature.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-family:inherit\">Birman cats do not reach full maturity until they are 3 years old.</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 1682145201, 1683266176, 2, NULL),
(63, 'American Shorthair Cat', 'american-shorthair-cat', 'licensed-image.jpg', '<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(74, 69, 66); font-family:antenna,arial,helvetica neue,helvetica,sans-serif\">Formerly used to keep rodents and vermin away from food stores, the American Shorthair still enjoys exercising her hunting skills on unsuspecting insects. As a smart, moderately active feline, she enjoys learning tricks and challenging her intelligence with puzzles and interactive toys.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Temperament</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">She&rsquo;s adaptable and good-natured, which makes her the ideal family companion. Although she loves attention from her people, including children, the American Shorthair does not like being carried and is fairly independent. She may curl up in your lap on occasion, but she may prefer to sit alongside you instead. She&rsquo;ll get along fine with a cat-friendly dog, but her hunting instincts may take over with pet birds and other small animals.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Characteristics</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">As a working cat, American Shorthairs have a stocky, muscular build. Their muscular legs lend themselves to the American&rsquo;s agility and endurance. They have a large head and full face, medium-sized ears, and large, wide eyes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Lifespan</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">15 to 20 years</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Colors</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">American Shorthairs are a diverse breed with an array of colors and patterns. Silver tabby is one of the most common and popular, however.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Shedding</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Your American Shorthair will shed but combing a couple of times per week removes dead hair and redistributes skin oils to keep her coat shiny and prevent dry, itchy skin.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Health</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The American Shorthair is a hearty and healthy breed. Some instances of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy have been recorded, but it&rsquo;s unknown if the condition is hereditary. Their flat face also makes the breed more susceptible to ocular and respiratory issues. They are genetically predisposed to mouth and gum disease and their laid-back nature increases their risk of obesity. Reputable breeders test thoroughly to avoid breeding cats with genetic diseases.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Choosing the Best Food for American Shorthair Cats</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Because American Shorthairs are generally healthy, a portion of complete and balanced cat food should be sufficient for their needs. If your American puts on weight due to inactivity, however, you may want to consider a healthy weight formula like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-weight-management-chicken-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\"><span style=\"color:#2F4F4F\">Purina Pro Plan Adult Weight Management Formula</span></a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/purina-one/cats/healthy-weight-cat-food\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Purina ONE Healthy Metabolism</a>, and if she regularly develops hairballs, consider a specially formulated cat food to help control them, such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-hairball-control-chicken-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Purina Pro Plan Hairball Management Chicken &amp; Rice Formula</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">To explore other products for your American Shorthair, see our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-products/product-selector\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Product Selector</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Choosing the Best Food for American Shorthair Kittens</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Like several other breeds, American Shorthairs are slow to mature, with many not reaching their full size until 3 or 4 years of age. To support your American kitten&rsquo;s growth and development, select a complete and balanced kitten food such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-kitten-chicken-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Purina Pro Plan Kitten Chicken &amp; Rice Formula</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/purina-one/cats/dry-cat-food/healthy-kitten-food\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Purina ONE Healthy Kitten Formula</a>&nbsp;during her first year or so of life. Switch her to a complete and balanced adult cat food after her first birthday.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>History</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">American Shorthairs may have descended from other domestic shorthairs brought over on the Mayflower in 1620, or even earlier by the first settlers of Jamestown or even Spanish explorers in Florida. A 1634 publication credits these domestic shorthairs with saving New England crops from squirrels and chipmunks. They were exhibited at the first U.S. cat show in 1895 and Cat Fanciers Association (CFA) recognized them as a founding breed in 1906.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Facts</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The breed wasn&rsquo;t called &ldquo;American Shorthair until 1966 when it was given the name to distinguish it from other domestic shorthairs and random-bred shorthairs.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Because they resemble so many other domestic shorthair cats, the only way to know yours is American is with certified breed papers.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">An American Shorthair was named CFA&rsquo;s &ldquo;Cat of the Year&rdquo; in 1965, 1984, and 1996.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 1683262515, 1683682867, 2, NULL),
(65, 'Bengal', 'bengal', 'cats.jpg', '<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(74, 69, 66)\">Bengal Cats are curious and confident with the tameness of a domestic tabby and the beauty of an Asian Leopard Cat. Learn more about Bengals and their playful personality, plus information on their health and how to feed them.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Characteristics</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Bengal Cats have an athletic appearance with well-defined muscles, creating a lean, balanced appearance. They feature high cheekbones, dark markings around the eyes and the ears are small and pointed but round at the tips. Their coats have a unique, plush feel unlike any other cat breed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Lifespan</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">12 to 16 years</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Colors</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">One of the most distinctive features of this feline is its unique coat pattern and color. Most Bengal Cats&rsquo; coats have rich, highly contrasted shades of bright orange to light brown, with dark spots or a distinctive marbling pattern. Some even have a &ldquo;glitter&rdquo; to the tips of their fur, which glistens when the light hits it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Shedding</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">A Bengal is fairly low maintenance. She won&rsquo;t shed much and is an efficient self-groomer.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Health</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Although responsible breeders make every effort to avoid health complications and genetic disorders in their felines, there are some conditions you should be aware of.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Bengals may suffer from distal neuropathy and flat-chested kitten syndrome, both of which typically resolve on their own as the kitties mature. As they age, Bengals may develop other problems like hip dysplasia, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, patellar luxation, and progressive retinal atrophy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Choosing the Best Food for Bengal Cats</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Because of their energetic nature, Bengals need a complete and balanced cat food rich in protein, such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/savor-cat-food\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Complete Essentials</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/true-nature-high-protein-cat-food\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan True Nature</a>&nbsp;dry and wet food. Always consult with your veterinarian if you have any questions or concerns, and slowly transition your feline companions to a new food to avoid digestive upset.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">To explore other products for your Bengal Cat, see our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-products/product-selector\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Product Selector</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Choosing the Best Food for Bengal Kittens</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Bengal kittens need additional nutrients to support their growth and development. Consider a kitten food like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/kitten-food\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Development Kitten</a>&nbsp;dry and wet products or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/true-nature-high-protein-cat-food?f[0]=life_stage%3A1471\" style=\"color: rgb(183, 32, 37); margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan True Nature Kitten Grain Free</a>&nbsp;dry and wet products to provide your kitty everything she needs to reach her full potential.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>History</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Bengal Cat is a hybrid of a domestic cat with the wild Asian Leopard Cat. The first crossbreed was performed by Jean Mill in 1963, but the hybrid wasn&rsquo;t perfected until the mid-1980s. Today, Bengals are bred only with each other.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Facts</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Bengal Cat&rsquo;s name comes from the scientific name for the Asian Leopard Cat, Prionailurus bengalensis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Bengals are the only domestic cat with rosettes that resemble the markings on leopards, jaguars, and ocelots.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The International Cat Association (TICA) accepted the Bengal for championship status in 1991 and the American Cat Fanciers Association (ACFA) accepted the breed shortly thereafter.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The ACFA rescinded their acceptance after second-generation felines reportedly caused problems at cat shows. The Bengal was reinstated to ACFA in 1997 with the caveat that any cats shown had to be fifth the generation.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 1683265145, 1683680755, 2, NULL),
(66, 'Maine Coon Cat Breed', 'maine-coon-cat-breed', 'uploads/GettyImages-1189893683-e0ff70596b3b4f0687ba573e5a671f74.jpg', '<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(74, 69, 66)\">Maine Coon cats are gentle-natured and friendly, making them good companions. They are often tenderly playful and curious, making them kitten-like throughout their lives.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Characteristics</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The most recognizable characteristics of adult Maine Coon cats are their large size and long, bushy tail. Their paws are big and well-tufted to be suitable for walking in the snow, as can be seen in both adult and kitten Maine Coon cats. In addition, their ears are tufted, often with points of hair at the tips.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Lifespan</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">10 to 13 years</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Colors</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The most common color for Maine Coon cats is brown tabby. However, they can be nearly any color and pattern. Their eye colors, too, have a wide range from blue to green to gold and can include odd eyes (i.e. two different colored eyes).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Shedding</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The coat of a Maine Coon cat is shorter on the shoulders and longer on the stomach. It&rsquo;s smooth, shaggy and sheds moderately, though not more than other breeds with plush coats. While they do require frequent grooming, Main Coon cats love attention so they typically don&rsquo;t mind being brushed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Health</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Maine Coon cats are generally a hardy breed of cat. They&rsquo;re built for enduring cold, harsh New England winters. Maine Coons can suffer from hip dysplasia, with the abnormality affecting the larger males more than females.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Spinal muscular atrophy is a potential health problem that can result in muscle atrophy and weakness. This condition is normally seen early in the Maine Coon kitten&rsquo;s life. This feline is also more prone to developing hypertrophic cardiomyopathy than other breeds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Choosing the Best Food for Maine Coon Cats</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan cat food</a>&nbsp;offers several excellent options for feeding an adult Maine Coon Cat.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/wet-cat-food/complete-essentials-beef-chicken-gravy\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Purina Pro Plan Adult Beef &amp; Chicken Entr&eacute;e in Gravy</a>, for example, is high in protein and moisture content.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">To explore other products for your Maine Coon, see our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pet-food-finder\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Product Selector</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Choosing the Best Food for Maine Coon Kittens</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">For Maine Coon kittens, choose a food specially formulated for a kitten&rsquo;s needs, like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/wet-cat-food/development-kitten-ocean-whitefish-tuna-flaked\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\"><span style=\"color:#696969\">Purina Pro Plan Kitten Ocean Whitefish &amp; Tuna Entr&eacute;e</span></a><span style=\"color:#696969\">.</span> The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/kitten-food\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan</a>&nbsp;line offers many options, including both wet and dry food, specifically formulated to meet a kitten&rsquo;s needs during her formative years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">If you so desire, you can feed Maine Coon cats and kittens dry food in place of wet or as a supplement to occasional wet feedings. Always make sure there is plenty of fresh water available, of course.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">History</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Many folktales surround the history of Maine Coon cats. Some involve Marie Antoinette, others surround an English seafarer named Captain Coon. One genetically impossible myth claims Maine Coons are the result of domestic cats mating with raccoons.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">It is believed Maine Coon cats are descendants of domestic short-haired cats that bred with Scandinavian cats brought to North America by Norsemen. As such, the Maine Coon cat may be related to the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-breeds/norwegian-forest-cat\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Norwegian Forest Cat</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Facts</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">In 1985, this all-American breed became the official state cat of Maine.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The winner of the first cat show in North America, at Madison Square Garden in 1895, was a Maine Coon cat.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Maine Coon is not a cross between a cat and a raccoon.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 1683266082, 1683682819, 2, NULL),
(67, 'Persian', 'persian', 'uploads/GettyImages-181861505-4e63227ed0a14dc9bfe86848ef54caf3.jpg', '<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"color:rgb(74, 69, 66)\">The docile Persian is a quiet feline who enjoys a calm and relaxing environment. Although she enjoys sitting in her humans&rsquo; laps and being pet, she&rsquo;s just as happy to sit and observe everyone&rsquo;s comings and goings from afar. Persians are independent and selective in who they show affection.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Temperament&nbsp;</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">They enjoy playful activities but are also content to drape themselves over an armchair rather than attempt to climb atop a bookcase. Persian kitties do well with mild-mannered children and laid-back dogs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Characteristics</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Persian kitty has some distinct features, including a round head with a short face and snub nose. She also has chubby cheeks, big, round eyes and small, rounded ears. Persians have short, strong legs to support their sturdy bodies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Lifespan</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">15 to 20 years</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Colors</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The original Persian Cat had shiny, gray fur. Due to selective breeding, however, they now boast an array of different colors. In fact, there are 7 different coat color divisions total for competition purposes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">These range from silver and gold to white, smoky, and solid-colored. Their eye color corresponds to their coat color. For example, white Persians tend to have deep blue or copper eyes, whereas silver or golden Persians have green eyes, and solid-colored cats have copper eyes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Shedding</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Although they can shed a lot, proper grooming will prevent your Persian kitty from leaving hair all over your home. Comb her hair daily to prevent tangles and matting and to remove loose hair. Bathing once per month (after a thorough combing) will keep her coat and skin healthy and dirt free.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Health</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Persian&rsquo;s facial structure can predispose her to a number of potential health complications, including:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Respiratory difficulties</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Misaligned teeth</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Eye conditions like excessive watering and entropion</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Heat sensitivity</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Persians are also more susceptible to ringworm (because of their long coats), skin conditions that cause itching, redness and hair loss and polycystic kidney disease. Responsible breeders dedicate themselves to breeding healthy Persian Cats who are no more prone to illness and disease than other breeds, however.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Choosing the Best Food for Persian Cats</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The flat face and short jaw of your Persian kitty may make it more difficult for her to eat dry kibble and drink enough water. Consider giving her a dry cat food like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/purina-one/cats/dry-cat-food/hairball-formula\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\"><span style=\"color:#696969\">Purina ONE Hairball Formula</span></a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-hairball-control-chicken-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Specialized Hairball Management Chicken &amp; Rice Formula</a>&nbsp;and supplementing with a wet cat food such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-indoor-care-salmon-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Specialized Indoor Salmon &amp; Rice Formula</a>. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">This will help ensure your Persian is getting all the nutrients she needs, while helping control hairballs caused by her long and luscious coat. When it comes to selecting a feeding bowl, opt for a wide, shallow dish or saucer with low sides.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">To explore other products for your Persian, see our&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/cats/cat-products/product-selector\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Product Selector</a>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>Choosing the Best Food for Persian Kittens</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">You&rsquo;ll want to keep those chewing problems in mind when selecting kitten food. In addition to being easy to eat and supporting hydration, it should also include essential nutrients your Persian kitty will need for her growth and development throughout her first year of life. A kitten food such as&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/wet-cat-food/focus-kitten-salmon-ocean-fish\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Kitten Salmon &amp; Ocean Fish Entr&eacute;e Ground</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/wet-cat-food/focus-kitten-ocean-whitefish-tuna-flaked\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Kitten Whitefish &amp; Tuna Entr&eacute;e Flaked</a>,&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.purina.com/pro-plan/cats/dry-cat-food/focus-kitten-chicken-rice\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-top-style: initial; border-right-style: initial; border-bottom-style: solid; border-left-style: initial; border-top-color: initial; border-right-color: initial; border-bottom-color: transparent; border-left-color: initial; border-image: initial; font-weight: inherit; font-style: inherit; font-family: inherit; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(183, 32, 37); cursor: pointer; transition: color 0.25s ease 0s, border-color 0.25s ease 0s;\">Pro Plan Kitten Chicken &amp; Rice Formula</a>&nbsp;will provide complete and balanced nutrition for your growing Persian kitty.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:18px\"><strong>History</strong></span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Persian Cats originated in Mesopotamia, which later became Persia and is now modern-day Iran. Their soft features and docile personality attracted the attention of Pietro Della Valle, an Italian nobleman who is credited with bringing these felines to Europe in the 17<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century. The Persian kitty was a favorite of Queen Victoria and the breed was imported to the U.S. in the late 19<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size:18px\">Facts</span></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">Modern Persian Cats are available in over 80 different color combinations.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">The Persians participated in the first modern cat show, which took place in London in 1871.</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size:14px\">There was a push in the U.S. to make the Silver Persian its own breed called &ldquo;Sterling&rdquo;. This was rejected, however, and silver and goldens are considered within the Persian category at cat shows.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 1683266469, 1683682782, 2, NULL);
